<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Now, I am admittedly not terribly knowledgeable in the matter of nuclear power -- but from what I understand, it does not release polution into the world, but it does store loads of nuclear waste. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, yes and no.  Most of the material that is now termed &quot;nuclear waste&quot; falls into two categories, high level and low level.<br>
<br>
High level waste is MEAN STUFF, make no mistake, but the volume of it is tiny compared to the amount of waste generated by burning coal or oil.  Plus, most of the stuff that is classified as high level waste is actually partially consumed nuclear fuel.  If we would approach it sensibly and simply recycle it, it would not be waste at all, it would be more fuel.<br>
<br>
Low level waste is produced in much greater volume, but it is &quot;dangerous&quot; by only the most strict interpretation.  Low level waste is such stuff as the clothing used by nuclear workers and old tools which have been mildly activated by neutron exposure.  Low level waste can be handled by simply stuffing it into a landfill and letting it age gracefully.<br>
<br>
Compare this to the gigatons of Carbon Dioxide emitted by burning hydrocarbons, plus the particulates, poisonous oxides, heavy metals, etc.  For example, coal fired plants in the USA release thousands of pounds of Uranium straight into the air EVERY DAY.   Reactors don't do this, to put it mildly.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Correct? So if a nuclear plant was secure enough, would it not be fairly safe? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
